column3: The meatpacking factory had found many solutions to use or cover up spoiled meat. For instance, when meat that was taken out of pickle was "found sour," instead of scrapping the meat, the company decided to "...rub it up with soda to take away the smell, and sell it to be eaten on free lunch counters" (Sinclair). In addition, when hams that were pickled were found spoiled, some of them with, "...an odor so bad that a man could hardly bear to be in the room with them," (Sinclair), a second pickle would instead be pumped into the same meat, which destroyed the odor. This process, so often used in the meatpacking industry, became known to the workers as "giving them thirty per cent" (Sinclair). Lastly,  the industry would relabel products after working on the meat to make the odor, bacteria, or old parts of the meat go away, creating products such as "boneless hams", which were "odds and ends of pork stuffed into casings," or even "skinned hams," labeled as fancy, which were made of the oldest pigs, with heavy and coarse skin, "...that no one would buy-that is, until they had been cooked and chopped fine and labeled "head cheese!"" (Sinclair).
column4: The passage describes the meatpacking industry's methods of dealing with spoiled meat. The methods can be quite peculiar and often result in the disposal of the meat.

column4: The Egyptian social structure was a hierarchical system, with the gods at the top, followed by the pharaohs, the nobles, priests, soliders, skilled workers, and last the people. The gods were believed to be responsible for the events in the world, and the pharaohs were considered to be extensions of the gods. The nobles were the only people who held government posts, while the priests were responsible for pleasing the gods. The soliders and skilled workers were responsible for protecting the country in war, with the skilled workers being physical experts. The population at the bottom of the social structure, the farmers and slaves, were forced to work in order to survive and were not paid for their labor.
